the gut","Rapid onset and short duration of action","Long context-sensitive half-time after infusion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAlfentanil has \u003Cstrong\u003Erapid onset and short duration of action\u003C/strong\u003E due to its relatively low lipid solubility compared to other opioids. This allows it to quickly cross the blood-brain barrier but not accumulate extensively in fatty tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh lipid solubility with slow onset of action\u003C/strong\u003E: Alfentanil actually has lower lipid solubility than other opioids like fentanyl, which enables its rapid onset of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary renal route of elimination\u003C/strong\u003E: Alfentanil undergoes hepatic metabolism via cytochrome P450 3A4 as its primary route of elimination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtensive first-pass metabolism in the gut\u003C/strong\u003E: While some first-pass metabolism occurs, this is not a major characteristic of alfentanil\u0027s pharmacokinetics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong context-sensitive half-time after infusion\u003C/strong\u003E: Alfentanil maintains a short context-sensitive half-time even with prolonged administration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese properties make alfentanil particularly useful for short procedures and when rapid recovery is desired.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alfentanil is an opioid analgesic with rapid onset and short duration of action due to its low lipid solubility.","The context-sensitive half-time of alfentanil remains short even after prolonged infusion.","Alfentanil is metabolised primarily by cytochrome P450 3A4 in the liver."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54452"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16810"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54452"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T19:44:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T19:45:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9501"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68995"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemC